SIMPLE: idol
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Idol
<hw>I"dol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>idole</ets>,
F. <ets>idole</ets>, L. <ets>idolum</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ that
which is seen, the form, shape, figure, fr. <?/ to see. See
<er>Wit</er>, and cf. <er>Eidolon</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An image
or representation of anything.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do her adore with sacred reverence,⟦br⟧
As th' <qex>idol</qex> of her maker's great magnificence.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An image of a divinity; a representation or symbol
of a deity or any other being or thing, made or used as an object of
worship; a similitude of a false god.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That they should not worship devils, and <qex>idols</qex> of
gold.</q> <rj><qau>Rev. ix. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That on which the affections are strongly (often
excessively) set; an object of passionate devotion; a person or thing
greatly loved or adored.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soldier's god and people's <qex>idol</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A false notion or conception; a fallacy.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>idols</qex> of preconceived opinion.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Idolastre</ent>⟦br⟧
